  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "ITALY",
    "content": "Agent?—England. Britain’s strategy is maritime caution: protect sea lanes, avoid overcommitment on land. With France likely to act aggressively (60% per our forecast artifact), instability in the west could create opportunities in the Mediterranean. I advise you to hold Italy’s current positions but be prepared to exploit any French distraction—I'll keep SPA/POR secure and out of opportunistic Franco-Italian clashes. If you seek a temporary maritime understanding (nonaggression in Gascony/Marseilles axis), I will refrain from supporting French coastal moves from the Bay of Biscay. Confirm if you accept a mutual hands-off for S1915M."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "global",
    "content": "To all: England speaks plainly—my priority is stable seas and preventing a continental hegemon. Forecast implication: our STORYWORLD_FORECAST_ARTIFACT marks France as 60% likely to act aggressively next phase; I treat this as a trigger for measured, coalition-minded responses (confidence 0.6). I will hold BEL/HOL/DEN to secure the Channel and North Sea, and I seek short, reversible understandings with neighbors so no single power can exploit a French move to dominate Europe. If any power wishes to discuss precise orders, timing, or mutual nonaggression guarantees that preserve naval freedom-of-action, state your intent and probable moves for S1915M (quantify if possible) so I can set fleet-anchoring orders to minimize accidental escalation."
  }
]

